New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's assume the leading world politicians would once again meet in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
They would naturally focus first on today's problems: the crisis in the eurozone, the global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, addressing these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the overall solidity of the world economic arrangements.
Here are seven common-sense principles for global economic governance on which they might possibly agree.
(I discuss this in greater detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. Markets must be deeply embedded in existing regulatory systems.
The idea that markets regulate themselves has suffered a fatal blow through the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other societal institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies to establish and enforce rules.
They depend on the stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They require the political acceptance generated by progressive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all this applies equally to global markets.
2. In the foreseeable future, a democratic state system is likely to be largely organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives, even if it may be somewhat weakened, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is futile.
It is hardly to be expected that national governments would cede significant control to transnational institutions; moreover, a harmonization of rules would be of no benefit to societies with different needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems to contradict it.
Too often, we squander international cooperation on overly ambitious goals, resulting ultimately in weak outcomes that represent the smallest common denominator among the major countries.
When international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the WTO rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic processes within our own countries, rather than undermining them.
The pursuit of a world government is considered unrealistic.
3. Pluralistischer Wohlstand: The admission that the central institutional infrastructure of the global economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The United States, Europe, and Japan have long-term comparable prosperity.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social safety nets, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models"—one for each decade—is then presented as the great success to which one should aspire.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experiments and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A global economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will tend to promote rather than suppress such experimental openness and evolutionary development.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may appear innocuous.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing views of globalization advocates.
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the means to shape and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to "protect" them.
Therefore, we should accept that countries may retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect the health and safety of consumers – and that they should be allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders when trade is demonstrably threatening domestic practices that enjoy broad public support.
If globalization advocates are right, the call for such protective measures will fail due to a lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve to ensure that conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations – both receive adequate attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules within one's own country is not to be confused with the use of such restrictions to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
They should not also allow the United States or the EU to use trade sanctions or other forms of pressure to change labor market rules, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.
Therefore, we should accept that countries may retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect the health and safety of consumers – and that they should be allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders when trade is demonstrably threatening domestic practices that enjoy broad public support.
6. International agreements on economic cooperation to regulate the interaction between national institutions: Relying on the fact that nation-states provide the basic governance functions of the global economy does not mean that we should do without international rules.
The Bretton Woods system ultimately also had clear rules, although these were limited in scope and depth.
A complete free-for-all would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the global economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot count on the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually takes place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Therefore, less liberal rules must apply to undemocratic states.
These are the principles that the architects of the next global economic order must accept.
The most important thing is that they must accept the ultimate paradox illustrated by each of these principles: globalization works best when it is not pushed too far.
